  "text": "sion of STAT4 and low basal responsiveness to type 1 IFNs for pSTAT4 activation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . They can be stimulated through their T cell receptor (TCR) for antigen to express IFN-␥ by using STAT4-independent pathways [CITATION_3] . At times of peak expansion during acute lymphocytic choriomeningitis virus (LCMV) infection in vivo, however, the LCMV-specific CD8 T cells have elevated STAT4 [CITATION_4] with sensitivity to type 1 IFNs and IL-18 [CITATION_5] , as well as IL-12 [CITATION_6] , for IFN-␥ induction ex vivo and respond with IFN-␥ Responses to cytokine or TCR stimulation ex vivo were examined as indicated after 24 h in culture under control conditions (medium), after treatment with IFN-␣ at 1,000 U/ml, IL-12 at 10 ng/ml, or IL-18 at 10 ng/ml alone and combinations of IFN-␣ and IL-18 (B, C, E), with plate-bound antibodies against CD3 (␣CD3) (E, F), and with pooled immunodominant LCMV peptides, i.e., NP396, GP276, and GP33 (F). (B, E, F) Induction of IFN-␥ (green) was evaluated by intracellular staining, and that of CD25 (red) was evaluated by cell surface staining. Gray-shaded histograms are results of staining under control conditions. (C) Responses of day 8 LCMV-Tet ϩ (color-shaded histograms) compared to LCMV-Tet Ϫ (gray-shaded histograms) CD8 T cells are shown. Histograms are results from an individual mouse. Values are mean results Ϯ SEMs obtained with four mice per group in one experiment. The experiments were repeated twice. Significant differences between the responses of WT and STAT4 Ϫ groups are indicated as follows: ***, P Յ 0.0001; **, P Յ 0.005.",
